 So I read pretty thoroughly the animal research on T3 and saw that the brain,

00:52:05.000 --> 00:52:08.000
 regardless of what is happening in your bloodstream,

00:52:08.000 --> 00:52:14.000
 the brain usually keeps a ratio of one to one, T4 to T3,

00:52:14.000 --> 00:52:20.000
 even though the bloodstream might have 40 or 50 times more T4 than T3.

00:52:20.000 --> 00:52:24.000
 The brain requires practically equal amounts to function.

00:52:24.000 --> 00:52:31.000
 And an experimenter took slices of brain tissue in a dish measuring their oxygen consumption

00:52:31.000 --> 00:52:40.000
 and showed that when thyroxine was added to the slice, the oxygen consumption decreased,

00:52:40.000 --> 00:52:45.000
 which is exactly the opposite of what T3 does when it's added to a tissue.

00:52:45.000 --> 00:52:52.000
 So this is apparently what happens when someone goes into a coma while taking huge doses of thyroxine

00:52:52.000 --> 00:52:57.000
 or starts hallucinating when they're increasing their plain T4 dose.

00:52:57.000 --> 00:53:06.000
 It's reaching such a concentration that the brain can no longer maintain its one to one ratio of T4 to T3.

00:53:06.000 --> 00:53:15.000
 And so it's actually displacing the T3 and causing hypothyroid symptoms because T3 is the active hormone.

00:53:15.000 --> 00:53:20.000
 What does that mean that most of us who are hypothyroid should be looking at something like,

00:53:20.000 --> 00:53:24.000
